вҠў generate-article
  given topicвҶ’title вүЎ "The History of Version Control Systems"
  given topicвҶ’scope вүЎ "From early mainframe source management through distributed version control. Cover SCCS, RCS, CVS, Subversion, BitKeeper, Git, and Mercurial. Focus on factual milestones: creation dates, creators, key technical innovations."
  yield article-text, claims[]

  вҲҙ Write a concise article (6-8 paragraphs). Extract every factual claim.

-- LLM evaluation:
-- Writing article covering VCS history from 1972 to present day.
-- Extracting verifiable factual claims from each paragraph.

  yield article-text вүЎ "The History of Version Control Systems

The need to track changes in source code emerged alongside the earliest software projects. In the 1970s, programmers at Bell Labs faced the challenge of coordinating modifications to large codebases. Marc Rochkind created SCCS (Source Code Control System) in 1972 at Bell Labs, making it the first widely recognized version control system. SCCS stored deltas вҖ” the differences between file versions вҖ” rather than full copies, an innovation that made version tracking practical on storage-constrained mainframes.

A decade later, Walter Tichy at Purdue University released RCS (Revision Control System) in 1982. RCS improved on SCCS by storing reverse deltas, keeping the most recent version in full and computing older versions on demand. This made checkout of the latest revision faster, which matched typical developer workflows. RCS remained file-oriented, however вҖ” each file had its own version history with no concept of a project-wide snapshot.

The limitation of single-file versioning drove Dick Grune to create CVS (Concurrent Versions System) in 1986. CVS introduced the copy-modify-merge model, allowing multiple developers to edit the same file concurrently and reconcile changes later. It built on top of RCS for file-level storage but added a client-server architecture and the concept of a repository containing an entire project. CVS became the dominant open-source version control system throughout the 1990s.

By the early 2000s, CVS's architectural limitations вҖ” no atomic commits, no rename tracking, no directory versioning вҖ” became acute. CollabNet founded the Subversion (SVN) project in 2000, with Karl Fogel and Jim Blandy leading the initial development. Subversion 1.0 shipped in 2004 and addressed CVS's core deficiencies: it provided atomic commits, versioned directories, and efficient branching through cheap copies. Subversion used a centralized model with a single authoritative repository.

The shift to distributed version control began with BitKeeper, created by Larry McVoy in 1998. BitKeeper was used to manage the Linux kernel source from 2002 to 2005 under a controversial proprietary license. When Andrew Tridgell reverse-engineered the BitKeeper protocol in 2005, McVoy revoked the free license, precipitating a crisis in the kernel development community. This event directly motivated Linus Torvalds to create Git.

Linus Torvalds began writing Git in April 2005 and released the first version within weeks. Git's design prioritized speed, data integrity through SHA-1 content addressing, and support for distributed non-linear workflows. The system stored full snapshots of every committed state rather than deltas, using compression and packfiles for efficiency. Junio Hamano took over as Git maintainer in July 2005 and has led development since.

Around the same period, Matt Mackall released Mercurial in April 2005, also motivated by the BitKeeper crisis. Mercurial shared Git's distributed model but emphasized a simpler user interface and cross-platform compatibility. Both Git and Mercurial gained rapid adoption, but Git ultimately dominated, driven in large part by the launch of GitHub in 2008 by Tom Preston-Werner, Chris Wanstrath, PJ Hyett, and Scott Chacon. GitHub made Git accessible to a mass audience and established pull-request-based collaboration as the standard open-source workflow."

